abor, and the "growth machine" perspective. Going beyond the limitations of these and older theories, Gottdiener proposes a model of urban growth that accounts for the deconcentration away from the central city that began in the United States in the 1920s and continues today. Sociologists, political scientists, economists, geographers, and urban planners will find his interdisciplinary approach to urban science invaluable, as it is currently the most comprehensive treatment of European and American work in these related fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLand use. 0aMarxian economics. 0aMetropolitan areaszUnited States. 0aSociology, Urban. 0aSuburbszUnited States. 0aUrbanization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72772440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292751224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292751224/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK